Description. Length 9.0 mm (N= 2 ). Apical area of left pupal mandible with 4 subapical teeth, first 3 subequal, basal tooth larger; right mandible with 3 similar teeth subapically, with very small serrations basal to first basal tooth (
Fig. 13
). Hook plates (
Fig. 28
) present anteriorly on segments III–VII, posteriorly on segments III, IV and V. Hook plates IIIa each with 8–14 hooks, IIIp with 18–36 , IVa with 3 or 4 , IVp with 0, Va with 3–4 , Vp with 14–18 , VIa with 3–5 , and VIIa with 4–7 . Hook plates Vp oval with hooks very stout, pointing anterad; hook plates IIIp with hooks smaller, less stout (
Fig. 26
).

Abdominal apical processes yellowish brown, bifid, posterior lateral margins and concave caudal surfaces with numerous short spines, these spines on caudal surfaces increasing gradually in size apically (
Fig. 9 b
). Patch of black ls setae laterally at bases of apical processes. Several hl setae present on the anterodorsal margin of apical processes (
Fig. 9 a
). In caudal view apical margins of apical processes moderately concave (
Fig. 9 b
). Apical processes recurved anterodorsad slightly less than 90 ° to axis of body (
Fig. 9 a
). Apices of apical processes (
Fig. 9 b
) subequally long; in caudal view, lateral apices rounded, mesal apices acute.

Pupal case . Case length 10–13 mm , width 4 or 5 mm (N= 4 ). Case constructed entirely of small pebbles, gravel and sand, all tightly packed into an apparently continuous layer. The inner silk puparium enclosing pupa attached to smooth inner surface of stones. Case cylindrical with ends rounded (
Fig. 33
).
